Background & Life Story
I grew up in the Boston area and attended The Citadel for undergrad — a military college whose culture of discipline, structure, and honor left a lasting mark on how I move through the world. It's where I met my wife. After graduation we lived in New York City before I returned to school in Raleigh, North Carolina to pursue a Master's in Nutrition. During my graduate studies I began interning at RTI International, a nonprofit public health research institution, and have worked there ever since. My research has focused on food insecurity, healthcare, and substance use disorders. I'm 40 years old, married with two daughters (ages 4 and 8), and I live in Raleigh.

Professional Identity & Pursuits
By day I'm a programmer at a public health research institution, working primarily in SAS and R. But the fuller picture is this: I'm building an AI-powered mobile and web application called Arete — with the tagline "Be who you want to be" — designed to help people close the gap between who they are and who they are capable of becoming. I'm also a practicing Stoic philosopher, a boxer working toward my first amateur fight, and a writer. My professional ambitions are converging: I want to leave institutional research behind and build something of my own that is aligned with philosophy, personal development, and the life I'm actually trying to live.

Goals
My primary professional goal is to build and launch the Arete app — an AI-powered tool that helps people set and pursue goals, stay accountable, course-correct, and track genuine progress. Beyond the app, I want to master the skills required to build, ship, and scale a product from scratch. Long-term, I want to transition entirely out of institutional research into work that is meaningful to me and aligned with Stoic philosophy and human flourishing.
Personally, my goals are three: to pursue Stoic Sagehood as a direction — knowing the destination is essentially unreachable, but that the pursuit itself is the point. To become an excellent boxer, including an amateur fight if I can get there. And to achieve Arete in my own life — to flourish. To be as healthy, clear-minded, well-read, and virtuous as I am capable of being, and to exhibit courage, discipline, temperance, and wisdom every day.

Strengths
I am genuinely willing to change my mind when shown a better argument or a clearer truth. I don't cling to beliefs out of ego. I have six years of serious Stoic study and practice behind me — this is not a phase, it is a philosophy I live by and continue to deepen. My most reliable strength is commitment through constraint: I don't just decide to do something, I structure my circumstances so that I have to follow through. I don't just run — I sign up for marathons. I don't just cut back — I quit entirely. When I burn the boats, I don't look back. I have a proven track record of recovering from major adversity and emerging stronger each time.

Weaknesses
Without external structure and accountability, my follow-through can falter — especially on longer-horizon projects that don't have a clear finish line or deadline. I doubt myself and my ideas, and that inner critic can quietly kill momentum before a project ever gets started. I'm also all-or-nothing by nature: I either go all in or I disengage. This is a superpower in the right circumstances and a liability when a goal requires patience, gradual progress, and sustained effort over months or years.

Patterns & Failure Modes
I go to extremes. I don't run — I train like David Goggins. I don't meditate — I want to sit for hours. This intensity is often a strength, but it can tip into overtraining, burnout, and eventual disengagement. Fatigue is my most reliable failure mode: when I'm tired, my discipline erodes and my self-doubt fills the gap. I also have an all-or-nothing tendency that means when I lose momentum I sometimes abandon things that only needed patience, not reinvention. The pattern I've noticed most clearly: my biggest derailments have always been followed by my biggest recoveries. I don't just come back — I come back better. But I need to be honest that the derailment is always a risk.
The feedback I respond to best is a mix of tough love and Socratic questioning. I often already see the right answer — I just need help accepting it and acting on it. Challenge my assumptions. Don't tell me what I want to hear. I have no interest in comfortable validation.

Major Life Events
2020 — COVID Pandemic: Found Stoicism while stuck in a pandemic funk. It changed the trajectory of my life.
2023 — My mother died of cancer. I leaned heavily on Stoic philosophy and physical discipline. This is when I began boxing.
2024–2025 — Major layoffs at RTI due to federal funding cuts. I quit drinking entirely and doubled down on my Stoic practice. The brain fog I had lived with for three decades lifted.
2026 — Completed my first marathon (Tobacco Road, March 15, 2026 — 3:49:58). The Arete app reached its first major milestone: working on both mobile and web with real-time sync.
Each crisis has been a crucible. I don't just survive adversity — I use it.

Future Self
I am 50 years old. I have built and launched the Arete app, and it is used by people around the world who are searching for direction and meaning in an era when AI has disrupted the economy and left many people without the structure that work once provided. I work a few deeply focused hours each day — because my discipline and clarity are sharp enough that I accomplish in three hours what others cannot do in ten. I am a great husband and father. I have mastered presence — not because life became easy, but because I practiced it long enough that it became who I am. Anger is not an emotion I experience — not because I suppressed it, but because I transformed it, over years, into fuel and eventually into peace. I am still boxing. I still train every morning. I read nearly a book a week. I am as close to a Stoic Sage as a human being can practically be. I look back at the man I was at 40 — working hard, doubting himself, building in the margins — and I recognize him. He did the work. That's why I'm here.
